20 Years Apart: Understanding the Evolution of the NBA Playoffs by Clustering¶

1. Executive Summary¶

National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most popular professional sports leagues in United States and Canada, and is considered to be the premier men's professional basketball league in the world. It has two components, and the one which is held after every NBA regular season is the Playoffs, to determine the league's champion. With this, it is of interest to analyze how the players have evolved its playstyle from the start of the previous decade (2000) up to the current. We also want to see the difference between the performance of players across years in comparison with the recent playoffs.


To answer this problem, the researchers looked into clustering the players based on their game stat totals using the data scraped from NBA website. The data includes only the NBA Playoffs starting from 2000 to 2019 and included only the first and last three years (of the scraped data) in the clustering.


K-means was used as the clustering algorithm since the dataset consists of mostly continuous variables with few features. Before the data was subjected to Kmeans, it was normalized first using the StandardScaler function from sklearn since the scales of the features largely differ from each other. After that, internal validation criteria particularly the Sum of Squares Distances to Centroids (SSE) was used to determine the optimal number of clusters for the dataset.


Results of the analysis showed that players of the NBA Playoffs can be grouped into 3 clusters: (1) Star players (2) Specialist / Role players (3) Players who rarely played during the playoffs. In addition, it was found out that there was a shift in the importance from defense to offense since in the early years, big men were given priority over shooters. However, in today's game, due to the rise of the Golden State Warriors and Stephen Curry, three (3) point shots were given more importance.

For future study, the researchers recommend to look at other decades and filter players with a certain threshold of number of games to eliminate the players that have small number of games played. They can also consider looking at the data of each player per possession or per 36 mins to better see the performance of each player.

2. Data Description¶

The dataset used in the study pertains to the Totals of the NBA Playoffs starting from 2000 to 2019 for a total of 20 years. This was scraped from https://www.basketball-reference.com/. Each row pertains to a unique player and each column pertains to the Stats measured per player. The data was divided into two groups: the first group ranges from 2000 to 2002 and the second group ranges from 2017 to 2019. The reason for the grouping is that we want to determine how the players evolve from the start of the previous decade (2000) up to now the current decade. There is also a separate analysis for the recent playoff (2019) to see the difference between the performance of players across decades in comparison with the recent playoffs. Listed below is the data dictionary for reference.

3.4. Data Cleaning¶

In cleaning the data, first, we replace all 0 values with Nan since we do not want to include empty data to the total number of observation. Also, when we try to get the datatype of each numerical column, it was automatically converted as an object datatype so we need to convert it to a float in order for us to use the values in the later calculation.

An important note on this is that each game stat in the dataset is on a per total basis of the playoffs. What we want to determine is the performance of the players per game because we might get the wrong idea if the games played was not considered. In order to account for this, we divide each game stat with the number of games played, and this calculation is shown in the function below together with the data cleaning.

In [465]:
def data_cleaning(df):
    
    df.replace(np.nan, 0.0, inplace=True)
    
    df.iloc[:, 4:] = df.iloc[:, 4:].astype(float)
    df['Age'] = df['Age'].astype(float)
    
    df_decade_byplayer = df.groupby('Player').sum()

    df_decade_byplayer_dropped = df_decade_byplayer
    
    # Recalculating percentages
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FG%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FG']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FGA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3P%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3P']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3PA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2P%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2P']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2PA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FT%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FT']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FTA']
    
    # Calculating per game stats
    stat_per_game = df_decade_byplayer_dropped.columns.to_list()[2:17]
    for stat in stat_per_game:
        df_decade_byplayer_dropped[stat] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped[stat]/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['G']
    
    return df_decade_byplayer_dropped

First is the plot of successful and attempted shots across years. Successful shots include free throws, 2-point shot and 3-point shot that was successfully made by the player whereas the attempted shots are those that both include missed and successful shots.

Based on the plots above, it can be seen that the trend for 2-point shot decreases for both Successful and Attempted shots while the trend for 3-point shot increases over time. For the Free throw shot, it also decreases for both successful and attempted shots. This just means that players tend to focus more on shooting 3-point shot starting from 2012 and lesser 2-point shot. This may be attributed to the era of Golden State Warriors and Stephen Curry which prioritizes 3-point shot rather than 2-point shot.

Rebounds, on the otherhand, can either be offensive or defensive. This indicates the player's ability to get possession which might lead to higher chances of scoring.

5. Methodology¶

This section covers the clustering of players based on their playstyle. It starts with selecting the features to be included in the clustering up to extracting the theme from the clusters formed.

5.1. Principal Components/Feature Selection¶


In selecting the features to be used in clustering, it is important to filter only those that have a great indicator of players' performance. Also, we do not want to include game stats that are just duplicates of the others especially in clustering because this might affect the result of the clusters. Instead of using Principal Components Analysis, feature selection is based on the researcher's domain knowledge. With this, from 31 features, only 11 features were used as part of the clustering.

Shown below is the function on how the features where selected.

In [479]:
def feature_engineering(df):
    
    df.replace(np.nan, 0.0, inplace=True)
    
    df.iloc[:, 4:] = df.iloc[:, 4:].astype(float)
    df['Age'] = df['Age'].astype(float)
    
    df_decade_byplayer = df.groupby('Player').sum()
    
    # Features to drop, since aggregating these are useless, TRB and PTS are useless
    to_drop = ['GS', 'MP', 'FG%', '3P%', '2P%', 'eFG%', 'FT%', 'TRB', 'PTS']
    
    # Creating a player to position mapping
    player_pos = {}
    for player in df_decade_byplayer.index.to_list():
        player_pos[player] = df.loc[df['Player'] == player]['Pos'].to_list()[0]
    
    # Dropping unnecessary columns
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped = df_decade_byplayer.drop(columns=to_drop)
    
    # Recalculating percentages
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FG%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FG']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FGA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3P%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3P']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['3PA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2P%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2P']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['2PA']
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FT%'] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FT']/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['FTA']
    
    # Calculating per game stats
    stat_per_game = df_decade_byplayer_dropped.columns.to_list()[2:17]

    for stat in stat_per_game:
        df_decade_byplayer_dropped[stat] = df_decade_byplayer_dropped[stat]/df_decade_byplayer_dropped['G']
        
    to_drop2 = ['FG', 'FGA', '3P', '3PA', '2P', '2PA', 'FT', 'FTA', 'Age', 'G']
        
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped_cluster = df_decade_byplayer_dropped.drop(columns=to_drop2)
    df_decade_byplayer_dropped_cluster.replace(np.nan, 0.0, inplace=True)
    return df_decade_byplayer_dropped_cluster, player_pos

5.2 Normalizing the data¶

Basketball game statistics vary in scales as there are some features which can have high values and others that can have only percentage as values. This would affect the result of the clusters if not properly handled. To account for this, we should normalize the data for all features which can be done using the StandardScaler method from sklearn. Normalizing the data changes only the values as it forces the mean to be equal to 0 and standard deviation to be equal to 1 without compromising the original distribution.

The code on how the data was normalized is shown below:

In [484]:

df_2019_tocluster_normed.index = df_2019_tocluster.index.to_list()

5.3 Clustering using Kmeans¶

To cluster the players based on their playstyle, KMeans Clustering procedure was used as it is known as the simplest and most popular representative-based clustering method. This method is useful in clustering data with few features of mostly continuous variables. The mean of the points in the cluster is chosen to be the representative for that cluster. In order to determine the optimal number of clusters to use, internal validation criteria was used and the theme extracted from the clusters formed were analyzed.

5.3.1. Determining the Optimal Number of Clusters (choose best k)¶

To determine the optimal number of clusters that best fits the data, internal validation criteria is used particularly the Sum of Squares Distance to Centroids (SSE).

  • Sum of Squares Distance to Centroids (SSE) - This corresponds to the sum of squares distances to the representative points. The smaller the values, the better is the clustering.

Below are the functions used in performing the internal validation criteria.

  • cluster_range - computes the cluster range from the given design matrix. It outputs a dictionary of cluster labels and internal validation values
  • plot_internal - plot of the results of the internal validation criteria

Since we have three sets of data and it is of interest to cluster each datasets, we should determine the optimal number of of clusters for each dataset. Shown below is the plot of SSE for the three datasets.

In [485]:
# Creating a cluster range for various k
def cluster_range(X, clusterer, k_start, k_stop):
    """Compute cluster range from the given design matrix

    Parameters
    ----------
    X : array
        Design matrix with each row corresponding to a point
    clusterer : 
        the clustering object
    k_start :integer
        starting number of clusters
    k_stop : integer
        ending number of clusters

    Returns
    -------
    validation : dictionary
        Dictionary of cluster labels, internal validation values and 
        actual labels
    """
    validation = {'ys': [],
                  'inertias': []
                 }

    for k in list(range(k_start, k_stop+1)):
        np.random.seed(11)
        kmeans_X = KMeans(
            n_clusters=k, random_state=clusterer.random_state)
        y_predict_X = kmeans_X.fit_predict(X)

        validation['ys'] += [y_predict_X]
        validation['inertias'] += [kmeans_X.inertia_]
        
    return validation
In [486]:
# Defining a function to plot each internal validation criteria
def plot_internal(inertias1, inertias2, inertias3):
    """Plot internal validation values"""
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(25,5))
    
    ks1 = np.arange(2, len(inertias1)+2)
    ax[0].plot(ks1, inertias1, '-o', label='SSE (Lower is better)')
    ax[0].set_title('SSE (Lower is better)', fontsize=15)
    ax[0].axvline(3, ls='--', c='k')
    ax[0].set_xlabel('$k$')
    
    ks2 = np.arange(2, len(inertias2)+2)
    ax[1].plot(ks2, inertias2, '-o', label='SSE (Lower is better)')
    ax[1].set_title('SSE (Lower is better)', fontsize=15)
    ax[1].axvline(3, ls='--', c='k')
    ax[1].set_xlabel('$k$')
    
    ks3 = np.arange(2, len(inertias3)+2)
    ax[2].plot(ks3, inertias3, '-o', label='SSE (Lower is better)')
    ax[2].set_title('SSE (Lower is better)', fontsize=15)
    ax[2].axvline(3, ls='--', c='k')
    ax[2].set_xlabel('$k$')

    return fig

Based on the plots above, it can be seen that for all datasets, the elbow occured when k = 3. This means that it is when the number of clusters is three that the sum of squares distance to centroids was minimized. Hence, the optimal number of clusters to be selected in Kmeans clustering is 3.

6. Clustering Proper¶

The section below discusses the clustering of players when k = 3. To determine the cluster of the actual players, the researchers appended the cluster number that was produced in the dataframe to help in separating the groups that was formed. With each player properly clustered, the most important features per cluster can be identified which will serve as the basis for extracting the theme observed in that cluster.

6.1. Clustering Players and Defining Clusters Formed¶

First, we define a function to cluster the multiple datasets that we have. Each dataset consists of the 2017-2019 combined playoffs data, 2000-2002 combined playoffs data and 2019 playoff data.

In [489]:
def clusterer(df, df_normed, player_pos):
    # Running k-means NORMALIZED
    k = 3

    k_means = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state = 1337)\
                            .fit(df_normed)

    df['Cluster'] = k_means.labels_

    cluster_list = {}
    for i in range(k):
        pos = []
        cluster_list[i] = df[df['Cluster']==i]
        for x in range(len(cluster_list[i])):
            pos.append(player_pos[cluster_list[i].iloc[x].name])

        cluster_list[i]['Pos'] = pos
        
    # Assign each cluster to a dataframe variable
    cluster0 = cluster_list[0]
    cluster1 = cluster_list[1]
    cluster2 = cluster_list[2]
    
    # Creating most important features mapper per cluster
    terms = df.columns[:-1]

    feat_list = []
    for i in range(k):
        feat_list_per_cluster = []
        for ind in k_means.cluster_centers_.argsort()[:, ::-1][i, :]:
            feat_list_per_cluster.append(terms[ind])

        feat_list.append(feat_list_per_cluster)

    weight_list = np.sort(k_means.cluster_centers_)[:,::-1].tolist()

    fw_fin = []
    for i in range(len(feat_list)):
        fw = []
        for feat, weight in zip(feat_list[i], weight_list[i]):
            fw.append((feat, weight))
        fw_fin.append(fw)
        
    return cluster0, cluster1, cluster2, feat_list[0], feat_list[1], feat_list[2], fw_fin

We then run the clusterers to each dataset.

What is interesting to note though is the difference between the playoff years of 2000-2002 with the playoff years of 2017-2019. The 2000-2002 playoffs put emphasis on blocks, 2-point percentages and defensive rebounds. This may be attributed to the fact that during the 2000s, big men or power forwards and centers were believed to be the winning formula for championships. An example of this was Shaquille O'neal's and the Los Angeles Lakers' dominance throughout these years. However, in today's game, especially in the 2017-2019 playoffs, there is emphasis on 3-point percentages which can be attributed to the rise of the Golden State Warriors and Stephen Curry.

Now let's visualize each cluster and try to see how the players were clustered for the years 2017-2019, 2000-2002 and 2019. To do this, we created a radar plot for each dataset and plotted the weight values of each feature for each cluster.

In [496]:
# Creating a radar dataframe
def radar_plot(fw_fin):
    radar = {'cluster' : ['0', '1', '2']}
    for i in range(len(fw_fin)):
        for x in range(len(fw_fin[i])):
            if fw_fin[i][x][0] not in radar.keys():
                radar[fw_fin[i][x][0]] = [fw_fin[i][x][1]]
            else:
                radar[fw_fin[i][x][0]].append(fw_fin[i][x][1])

    df_radar = pd.DataFrame(radar)

    return df_radar
In [497]:
def make_spider(fw_fin, row, title, color):
 
    # number of variable
    categories=list(radar_plot(fw_fin))[1:]
    N = len(categories)

    # What will be the angle of each axis in the plot? (we divide the plot / number of variable)
    angles = [n / float(N) * 2 * pi for n in range(N)]
    angles += angles[:1]

    # Initialise the spider plot
    ax = plt.subplot(1,3,row+1, polar=True, )

    # If you want the first axis to be on top:
    ax.set_theta_offset(pi / 2)
    ax.set_theta_direction(-1)

    # Draw one axe per variable + add labels labels yet
    plt.xticks(angles[:-1], categories, color='grey', size=8)

    # Draw ylabels
    ax.set_rlabel_position(0)
    plt.yticks([-1.5, -1, -0.5, 0, 0.5, 1, 1.5], ["-1.5", "-1", "0.5", "0", "0.5", "1","1.5"], color="grey", size=7)
    plt.ylim(-1.5,1.5)

    # Ind1
    values=radar_plot(fw_fin).loc[row].drop('cluster').values.flatten().tolist()
    values += values[:1]
    ax.plot(angles, values, color=color, linewidth=2, linestyle='solid')
    ax.fill(angles, values, color=color, alpha=0.4)

    # Add a title
    plt.title(title, size=11, color=color, y=1.1)

7. Conclusion¶

For the years 2017-2019, 2000-2002 and 2019, we were able to successfully cluster players according to their performance during the playoffs.

We were able to find an apparent pattern between the clusters. For each of the datasets, the three (3) clusters formed were:

  1. Star players
  2. Specialist / Role players
  3. Players who rarely played during the playoffs

A notable finding however is the shift of importance from defense to offense when comparing the most important features for the 2000-2002 and 2017-2019 datasets. Evident in the fact that for the years 2000-2002, blocks were given more importance as opposed to the years 2017-2019, where 3P% was given more importance. This can be attributed to the fact that during the early 2000s, big men were given priority over shooters. However, in today's game, due to the rise of the Golden State Warriors and Stephen Curry, three (3) point shots were given more importance.

8. Recommendation¶

For future study, the researchers recommend to look at other decades and filter players with a certain threshold of number of games to eliminate the players that have small number of games played. They can also consider looking at the data of each player per possession or per 36 mins to better see the performance of each player.
